            <h1>Governments, not private investors, own most of the fossil-fuel assets at risk.</h1>
            <h2>Global control of fossil-fuel production</h2>
            <div class="chart-sm"><img class="img-responsive" src="/img/govt-share.png" /></div>
            <p>The fossil-fuel value at risk from a low-carbon transition represents only 2-3% of the total value held by the owners of potentially stranded assets. Further, the largest share belongs to governments, who own over half of global fossil fuel production and control as much as 70% of oil and gas production through companies that are wholly or majority owned by governments. As governments control much of the policy that may lead to stranding, they can reduce impact and recover lost value through policy.</p>
